World Happiness Data

3/26/2020

Setting Up

library(tidyverse)
library(readxl)
library(lme4)
library(lmerTest)

Loading the Data and Data Wrangling

url1 <- "https://query.data.world/s/tw3oaknxjlqods27xzzbpa3do4rmfr"
p1f <- tempfile()
download.file(url1, p1f, mode="wb")
happy_data <- read_excel(path = p1f)

What is the range of years in the data?

happy_data$year %>%
  unique() %>%
  sort()
##  [1] 2005 2006 2007 2008 2009 2010 2011 2012 2013 2014 2015 2016

Renaming columns:

happy_data <- rename(happy_data, "LifeLadder" = `Life Ladder`)
happy_data <- rename(happy_data, "LifeExp" = `Healthy life expectancy at birth`)
happy_data <- rename(happy_data, "GDP" = `Log GDP per capita`)
happy_data <- rename(happy_data, "SocialSupport" = `Social support`)

Top 10 Countries for Happiness in 2016:

LifeLadder is the subjective happiness rating.

top_10 <- happy_data %>%
  filter(year == 2016) %>%
  group_by(country) %>%
  tally(LifeLadder) %>%
  top_n(10) %>%
  arrange(desc(n))
## Selecting by n
top_10
## # A tibble: 10 x 2
##    country         n
##    <chr>       <dbl>
##  1 Finland      7.66
##  2 Norway       7.60
##  3 Denmark      7.56
##  4 Netherlands  7.54
##  5 Iceland      7.51
##  6 Switzerland  7.46
##  7 Sweden       7.37
##  8 Australia    7.25
##  9 Canada       7.24
## 10 New Zealand  7.23

Plotting the Top 10:

top_10 %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = fct_reorder(country, n),
             y = n)) +
  geom_point() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(x = "Country",
       y = "Happiness Score",
       title = "Top 10 Happiest Countries in 2016")

Relationship between Happiness and Life Expectancy

Plotting the relationship:

happy_data %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = LifeExp,
             y = LifeLadder)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) + 
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(x = "Life Expectancy",
       y = "Happiness Score",
       title = "Relationship Between Life Expectancy and Happiness")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'
## Warning: Removed 9 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).
## Warning: Removed 9 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Building a model:

model1 <- lmer(LifeLadder ~ LifeExp + (1 | country) + (1 | year), data = happy_data)

Is there a consistent relationship between Life Expectancy and GDP?

happy_data %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = LifeExp,
             y = GDP)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) + 
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(x = "Life Expectancy",
       y = "GDP",
       title = "Relationship Between Life Expectancy and GDP") +

How is happiness affected by social support and generosity?

Filtering NAs for social support and generosity:

happy_data_new <- happy_data %>%
  filter(!is.na(happy_data$Generosity) & !is.na(happy_data$SocialSupport))

Correlation between social support and happiness:

happy_data_new %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = SocialSupport,
             y = LifeLadder)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) + 
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(x = "Social Support",
       y = "Happiness Score",
       title = "Relationship Between Social Support and Happiness")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Correlation between generosity and happiness:

happy_data_new %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Generosity,
             y = LifeLadder)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) + 
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(x = "Generosity",
       y = "Happiness Score",
       title = "Relationship Between Generosity and Happiness")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

The first one (social support) looks like a stronger relationship.

Building two models and comparing them:

model3 <- lmer(LifeLadder ~ SocialSupport + (1 | country) + (1 | year), data = happy_data_new)
model4 <- lmer(LifeLadder ~ Generosity + (1 | country) + (1 | year), data = happy_data_new)
## Warning in checkConv(attr(opt, "derivs"), opt$par, ctrl = control$checkConv, :
## Model failed to converge with max|grad| = 0.0020064 (tol = 0.002, component 1)
anova(model3, model4)
## refitting model(s) with ML (instead of REML)
## Data: happy_data_new
## Models:
## model3: LifeLadder ~ SocialSupport + (1 | country) + (1 | year)
## model4: LifeLadder ~ Generosity + (1 | country) + (1 | year)
##        Df    AIC    BIC  logLik deviance Chisq Chi Df Pr(>Chisq)
## model3  5 1597.5 1623.4 -793.75   1587.5                        
## model4  5 1715.5 1741.5 -852.77   1705.5     0      0          1

Happiness is more strongly predicted by social support than it is by generosity.
